And never have birth and fertility rates fallen so far, so fast, so low, for so long, in so many places, so surprisingly\" (p. 5).Wattenberg strangely omits death rates here as a factor in the computation of world population. They, together with birth rates, combine to yield total population levels and growth rates. And as for those death rates, we may also say: Never have the world's death rates fallen so far, so fast, so low, for so long, in so many places, as in the past 60 years. That is the one great factor that must always be kept in mind. It very largely negates Wattenberg's catchy alarmist sentence about falling birth rates.Wattenberg again: \"... [fertility] rates in the [less developed countries] are typically falling at a more rapid rate than ever experienced in the rich countries. And never have birth and fertility rates fallen so far, so fast, so low, for so long, in so many places, so surprisingly\" (p. 5).Wattenberg strangely omits death rates here as a factor in the computation of world population. They, together with birth rates, combine to yield total population levels and growth rates. And as for those death rates, we may also say: Never have the world's death rates fallen so far, so fast, so low, for so long, in so many places, as in the past 60 years. That is the one great factor that must always be kept in mind. It very largely negates Wattenberg's catchy alarmist sentence about falling birth rates.Wattenberg again: \"... [fertility] rates in the [less developed countries] are typically falling at a more rapid rate than ever experienced in the rich countries. As recently as 1970 the typical woman in a [less developed country] bore 6.0 children per woman. Today, in the midst of a fertility free-fall, the rate is about 2.8 or 2.7 children per woman and rapidly continuing downward\" (pp. 5-6).Yes, the fertility rates in less developed countries have fallen farther and more rapidly, but have done so because they were so very high to begin with. It is mind-boggling that Wattenberg can cite a birth rate of 6.0 without any apparent trace of concern, as if that were a fine status quo in an age when death rates are so very low. Moreover, how can he pretend to predict this \"rapidly continuing downward\" trend? He is thinking here like an obese man who has lost 50 pounds after a year of dieting and therefore blithely assumes he will lose another 50 in the next year, thus soon becoming slim and trim. Well, maybe - but maybe not. As a matter of fact, since Wattenberg wrote those words five years ago in 2003-04, the fertility rate has not declined much if at all in the less developed countries. It remains rather steady at about 2.7 to 2.8. And let's keep in mind that that group of less developed countries includes China (with all its 1.3 billion people), where the government's \"one child only\" policy has, since 1979, artificially kept its rate down (not to 1.0, but more like 1.8). That coercive policy puts a big dent in the fertility statistics of that group of developing countries, which would otherwise be much higher. Anyhow, five years is half a decade, of course. If Wattenberg expects the fertility rate in all of the less developed countries to drop to 2.1 within another few decades (actually, he predicts it will soon go down to 1.85 or even lower), the peoples of those countries had sure better start working on it right now. Moreover, the average fertility rate for the entire world (including the developed countries of Europe, etc.) today in early 2009 is about 2.6. That's right, for the Whole World, not just for the less developed countries. 2.6 is still quite high, considering that aforementioned low average death rate, and it means continuing population growth (e.g., another billion in merely the next decade or so).Wattenberg again: \"... Malthus? Two hundred years ago he wrote his famous essay on population, explaining that population growth would outpace food supply, causing famine and tragedy. He was wrong, and acknowledged it\" (p. 8).How can Wattenberg so categorically say that Malthus was \"wrong\"? Thomas Malthus, unlike Paul Ehrlich, made no specific predictions of mass famines sometime in the near future. Moreover, this is the first time that I have ever read anyone claim that Malthus \"acknowledged\" he was \"wrong.\" Malthus merely acknowledged the need to modify his theory, that's all. Time will tell whether he was right or wrong in a big way. Let's give him another 50 years of consideration at least.Wattenberg again: \"World population now numbers about six billion\" (p. 8).Wrong. In 2003-04, when Wattenberg was writing this book and these words, world population, as he very well knew, was already 6.3 to 6.4 billion and rapidly heading higher. In fact, when the hardcover edition of \"Fewer\" was published on October 25, 2004, world population was over 6.4 billion. So this deliberate understatement, \"six billion,\" was less than honest. Or maybe Wattenberg just forgot what that little figure of \".4\" billion means (400 million).Wattenberg again: \"That number [six billion] will grow to eight or nine billion.... Then population will decrease, perhaps by many billions\" (p. 9).Again we have Wattenberg's attitude of absolute certainty in this matter: \"... will grow to eight or nine billion.... Then population will decrease....\" Such certainty was questionable already when he was writing in 2003-04, and today in 2009 it appears to be actually refuted. The 2006 UN population revision, adjusting that low 2002 projection (but not enough, many of us think), projected as its medium variant at least 9.2 billion people by 2050, a number \"... increasing by about 30 million persons annually at that time\" (p. ix of \"Highlights,\" World Population Prospects: The 2006 Revision). The upper variant for 2050 is, according to that same 2006 revision, 10.8 billion, a far cry from Wattenberg's \"eight or nine billion.\" And that study also stresses the \"urgent\" need for expanded family planning facilities in the poorer countries of the world in order for those figures not to go even higher. There is no trace of such urgency in Wattenberg's breezy book. As for the \"decrease, perhaps by many billions\" that he foresees soon, that is unlikely to happen without strict government population policies worldwide.Wattenberg again: \"Alas, we do not know everything about those twenty-year-old potential mothers. We know roughly how many there will be in 2025, but we don't know how many children they will decide to bear. In the poor countries, they may have 3.0 children per woman, or perhaps only 2.0, or less\" (p. 9).Here Wattenberg blithely assumes that the average woman in all the poorer countries could soon, voluntarily, have only 2 children. He makes such blanket statements repeatedly throughout his book. His only justification for them is that women in richer countries have recently reduced the number of their children to 2 or fewer, and that women in some (but not even most) poor countries have done likewise. Yet, who is to say what the rest of the women of the world, that is, the majority of the women of the world, will do? If women, or rather couples, in poorer countries have always, for many centuries (and untold millennia before) averaged 5, 6, 7 or more children, isn't that a better figure to start with? Maybe many of them now, unless otherwise pressured by their governments, will continue to have at least 4 or 5 children for the next hundred years or more. And why does Wattenberg assume that it is only the women in those countries who \"will decide\" the matter? In vast numbers of poor countries, it is the men, the domineering men, who make the decisions in that regard. We all know the proud patriarchal logic: \"Big family, big man.\" And the miserable mothers bear the burden.Moreover, the family burden borne by such mothers today is far greater than ever before. In all of human prehistory, and in the vast majority of human history, most children died in infancy and early childhood, so the mothers only had the task of raising two or three of their several children to maturity. That has all changed now, due to modern medicine. Many women in the world today have to raise five, six, seven, or more children right up until they become adults themselves at around age 18. That's a huge new burden.Wattenberg again: \"[In 1987] the [total fertility rate] in the Developed Regions [e.g., Europe] had been falling steadily for thirty-five years. This was no short-term trend\" (p. 10).Meaning what? That the fertility rate in those regions will continue to fall lower and lower? But how low can it go? As of 2008 there was not a single country in the world, not even in Europe, whose fertility rate was below 1.0. But there were lots and lots of countries with rates still up around 4, 5, even 6 children per woman. Those are the ones we should be worrying most about - and doing most about.Wattenberg again: \"[In 2000-01] the United States, principally because of immigration, was growing steadily and would continue to do so. The UN medium variant projection called for about 400 million Americans by the year 2050....\" (p. 11).But what if that \"medium variant\" eventually proves to have been too low? What if the upper or medium-upper variants turn out correct instead? Oops! A slight mistake of 100 million or more. And in consequence we will instead have 500 million people in the USA by 2050, and no way to go back and warn people in the past (that is, people today) to change their immigration policies. With 500 million, many parts of the U.S. will be terribly crowded (just imagine Southern California, the Greater New York area, and South Florida with twice as many people as they have today). And one must also ask if Wattenberg's optimistically low 400 million estimate even includes the 30 million illegal immigrants that must also be reckoned with by then. And what about the total numbers in the year 2100, if the US remains very prosperous and therefore continually attracts more and more immigrants, as Wattenberg so fervently wants?Wattenberg again: \"[Also in 2000-01] the [total fertility rate] for the Less Developed Countries had fallen to 2.9 children per woman, from a high of 6 children in the late 1960s.... The end of worldwide population growth was thus clearly in sight....\" (p. 13).Here again Wattenberg is talking like an obese man who has lost 50 pounds fairly easily and then automatically assumes he will lose another 50 pounds just as quickly and easily. Not a wise assumption to make, especially since that group of less developed countries is not a small one, but comprises the majority of the world's population.Wattenberg again: \"Then, in March 2002.... the UN Population Division bit the bullet. Finally the world's official source showed as its medium projection that the Less Developed Countries would emulate the more developed nations and fall below replacement level\" (p. 14).\"Bit the bullet\"? Wattenberg makes it sound like this projection was a difficult one to make and was made by courageous people. Another real possibility is that the statisticians who made the projection were simply mistaken, or even that those statisticians, many of whom were from the Third World themselves, desperately wanted to feel good about the population situation in their own overcrowded countries and therefore easily leaped to the conclusion that a limited decline in Third World fertility rates in recent decades necessarily meant a continuing decline in the decades to come. But that is just not logical. It's a dangerous leap of faith. And why did they assume an \"emulation\" of some countries by all other countries? Why not assume, or at least allow for the possibility of, a competitive process of outbreeding, that is, the overrunning of some peoples by other peoples due to sheer fertility and population numbers? Were those statisticians ignorant of basic biology and evolution?Wattenberg again: \"[Also in 2002] The demographer from Iran reported that the [total fertility rate] in his officially Less Developed Country, a despotic Islamic theocracy, had already fallen to below 2.06 children per woman, that is, below replacement level\" (p. 14).So? Is Wattenberg suggesting that because one Islamic country has seen such a decline in its fertility rate, 30 other Islamic countries will soon follow suit? That was illogical in 2003, and his suggestion has certainly not been realized as of 2009. The Islamic world in general still has a very high fertility rate today. (Later, on p. 50, Wattenberg superficially mentions some other Islamic countries' slightly reduced fertility rates, and downplays their still high levels, claiming they are \"falling very rapidly\").Wattenberg again: \"Simply put, the UN had announced that henceforward [starting with the radical 2002 UN population projections] it would assume that average fertility in the poor countries would fall not just to 2.1 children per woman, as it had rigidly assumed through the 2000 volume. For the 2002 volume it would fall to 1.85.... All calculations in this book, unless otherwise noted, are based on that 2002 volume\" (p. 15).And that is why Wattenberg's book is so mistaken, because he relies so very heavily on that one study, and that extremely dubious 1.85 figure. It was a wrong-headed gamble to begin with, in 2003. He and the U.N. population researchers were trying to predict the near-future voluntary behavior of ALL the world's peoples based entirely on very recent past behavior by only some (not even half) of the world's other peoples. How irresponsible can you get?Wattenberg again: \"By definition, a species doesn't survive with an ongoing below replacement fertility rate\" (p. 16).Nor does any species survive with an unsustainably high fertility rate, far above replacement level and the resources available for it. That is the immediate problem still facing humanity today: overpopulation. Wattenberg's speculative, distant-future depopulation problem remains to be seen in the world as a whole.At the end of his first chapter, Wattenberg then writes: \"In coming years, I believe the [United Nations Population Division] will take its population and fertility projections even lower\" (p. 17).Such a belief was clearly flawed already in 2003, and by now, 2009, it appears to be quite wrong. The worldwide decline in fertility rates has slowed dramatically in recent years, as could and should have been predicted. It has declined from about 2.8 in 2000 to about 2.6 in 2008, or a mere .2 in eight long years. Again, the obesity analogy comes to mind. It is simply much more difficult for most people to lose those final extra pounds, and many people never do lose them. Indeed, many people, having once lost weight, gain some or all of it back. And it could be the same with fertility rates. After all, given the innate attraction between men and women, and their mutual wish for families, fertility rates can only go so low by voluntary means.So, that is one skeptic's analysis of Wattenberg's first chapter. Similar criticisms can be made of many of his other chapters (I have carefully read his book up to page 87 and have found his arguments mostly as weak as in Chapter 1). But I must admit that his second chapter, in which he details many of the reasons for the recent baby bust in Europe and Japan (and in the USA to some extent), seems largely accurate. However, I can't share his proposed solution: allowing more immigration from poorer countries into the richer ones. That might eventually only drag down the economies of Europe, Japan, and the USA, and would in any case eventually destroy their cultures. Why not let most of those would-be immigrants build up their own countries and cultures and economies?The true solution to the depopulation plight of the developed countries, and to the overpopulation plight of the Third World, is surely this: to increase fertility rates very slightly in the former, and to decrease them considerably in the latter. I'm sure that many people share this view. Sound policies can make it happen."

## [1] "I would really like to believe what Ben Wattenberg writes in this book \"Fewer\" about the prospects for world population. He thinks that overpopulation is no threat at all. Instead, he says that depopulation is our only cause for concern. But he isn't very persuasive, and seems to repeatedly hide or downplay the fact that there will be More, Many More people on this planet for quite some time (at least for decades, and probably for another century to come).Eventually, as Wattenberg writes, world population will go down. I wouldn't say that I \"agree\" with him on that point, as if he were the first one to mention it, because many of us recognized that fact decades ago, before ever hearing the name of Ben Wattenberg.World population must eventually decline simply because it cannot continue to go up and up and up forever. Nor can it conceivably stabilize at the levels it is projected to reach by 2050 or 2100, because those numbers, 9-10-11-12 billion, are simply not sustainable. The resources (water, food, oil, etc.) needed for so many people will just not be available. We may, for a brief time, increase our numbers even beyond 10 or 12 billion, but surely not for long. People will then fight and kill each other by the hundreds of millions, even billions, and/or will finally realize they must have far fewer children than ever before. Either way the numbers of humans will eventually go down. The only questions are When, What the peak number will be, and How miserable things will get before the decline starts and conditions eventually improve.However, let's now look more specifically at Wattenberg's book \"Fewer.\" Most of its 14 Amazon reader-reviewers so far have praised it highly. And one must also ask if Wattenberg's optimistically low 400 million estimate even includes the 30 million illegal immigrants that must also be reckoned with by then. And what about the total numbers in the year 2100, if the US remains very prosperous and therefore continually attracts more and more immigrants, as Wattenberg so fervently wants?Wattenberg again: \"[Also in 2000-01] the [total fertility rate] for the Less Developed Countries had fallen to 2.9 children per woman, from a high of 6 children in the late 1960s.... The end of worldwide population growth was thus clearly in sight....\" (p. 13).Here again Wattenberg is talking like an obese man who has lost 50 pounds fairly easily and then automatically assumes he will lose another 50 pounds just as quickly and easily. Not a wise assumption to make, especially since that group of less developed countries is not a small one, but comprises the majority of the world's population.Wattenberg again: \"Then, in March 2002.... the UN Population Division bit the bullet. Finally the world's official source showed as its medium projection that the Less Developed Countries would emulate the more developed nations and fall below replacement level\" (p. 14).\"Bit the bullet\"? Wattenberg makes it sound like this projection was a difficult one to make and was made by courageous people. Another real possibility is that the statisticians who made the projection were simply mistaken, or even that those statisticians, many of whom were from the Third World themselves, desperately wanted to feel good about the population situation in their own overcrowded countries and therefore easily leaped to the conclusion that a limited decline in Third World fertility rates in recent decades necessarily meant a continuing decline in the decades to come. But that is just not logical. It's a dangerous leap of faith. And why did they assume an \"emulation\" of some countries by all other countries? Why not assume, or at least allow for the possibility of, a competitive process of outbreeding, that is, the overrunning of some peoples by other peoples due to sheer fertility and population numbers? Were those statisticians ignorant of basic biology and evolution?Wattenberg again: \"[Also in 2002] The demographer from Iran reported that the [total fertility rate] in his officially Less Developed Country, a despotic Islamic theocracy, had already fallen to below 2.06 children per woman, that is, below replacement level\" (p. 14).So? Is Wattenberg suggesting that because one Islamic country has seen such a decline in its fertility rate, 30 other Islamic countries will soon follow suit? That was illogical in 2003, and his suggestion has certainly not been realized as of 2009. The Islamic world in general still has a very high fertility rate today. (Later, on p. 50, Wattenberg superficially mentions some other Islamic countries' slightly reduced fertility rates, and downplays their still high levels, claiming they are \"falling very rapidly\").Wattenberg again: \"Simply put, the UN had announced that henceforward [starting with the radical 2002 UN population projections] it would assume that average fertility in the poor countries would fall not just to 2.1 children per woman, as it had rigidly assumed through the 2000 volume. For the 2002 volume it would fall to 1.85.... All calculations in this book, unless otherwise noted, are based on that 2002 volume\" (p. 15).And that is why Wattenberg's book is so mistaken, because he relies so very heavily on that one study, and that extremely dubious 1.85 figure. It was a wrong-headed gamble to begin with, in 2003. He and the U.N. population researchers were trying to predict the near-future voluntary behavior of ALL the world's peoples based entirely on very recent past behavior by only some (not even half) of the world's other peoples. How irresponsible can you get?Wattenberg again: \"By definition, a species doesn't survive with an ongoing below replacement fertility rate\" (p. 16).Nor does any species survive with an unsustainably high fertility rate, far above replacement level and the resources available for it. That is the immediate problem still facing humanity today: overpopulation. Wattenberg's speculative, distant-future depopulation problem remains to be seen in the world as a whole.At the end of his first chapter, Wattenberg then writes: \"In coming years, I believe the [United Nations Population Division] will take its population and fertility projections even lower\" (p. 17).Such a belief was clearly flawed already in 2003, and by now, 2009, it appears to be quite wrong. The worldwide decline in fertility rates has slowed dramatically in recent years, as could and should have been predicted. It has declined from about 2.8 in 2000 to about 2.6 in 2008, or a mere .2 in eight long years. Again, the obesity analogy comes to mind. It is simply much more difficult for most people to lose those final extra pounds, and many people never do lose them. Indeed, many people, having once lost weight, gain some or all of it back. And it could be the same with fertility rates. After all, given the innate attraction between men and women, and their mutual wish for families, fertility rates can only go so low by voluntary means.So, that is one skeptic's analysis of Wattenberg's first chapter. Similar criticisms can be made of many of his other chapters (I have carefully read his book up to page 87 and have found his arguments mostly as weak as in Chapter 1). But I must admit that his second chapter, in which he details many of the reasons for the recent baby bust in Europe and Japan (and in the USA to some extent), seems largely accurate. However, I can't share his proposed solution: allowing more immigration from poorer countries into the richer ones. That might eventually only drag down the economies of Europe, Japan, and the USA, and would in any case eventually destroy their cultures. Why not let most of those would-be immigrants build up their own countries and cultures and economies?The true solution to the depopulation plight of the developed countries, and to the overpopulation plight of the Third World, is surely this: to increase fertility rates very slightly in the former, and to decrease them considerably in the latter. I'm sure that many people share this view. Sound policies can make it happen."

# Convert review text to corpus
corpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(df_tm$Review_text))

# Creating additional stopwords
myStopwords <- c(stopwords("en"),'will','want','just','well',"dont","even","thing","cant","still","really","every","take","tell","must",'make')
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower)) %>%
  tm_map(content_transformer(function(x) gsub("[^a-zA-Z ]", "", x))) %>% tm_map(removeWords, myStopwords) %>%
  tm_map(stemDocument)

#Term document matrix
tdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(corpus, control = list(wordLengths = c(4, 15)))

tdm_matrix <- as.matrix(tdm)

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is use to identify latent topics in the text and represent documents as as a mixture of this topics. LDA is applied to a transposed document term matrix, with the 7 number of topics.

dtm <- t(filtered_tdm_matrix)
lda_model <- LDA(dtm, k = 6)

Visualizing topics created by the model

#Creating a probability of each word in a topic
topics <- tidy(lda_model, matrix = "beta")

#Top 7 terms with highest probabliity
top_terms <- topics %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  top_n(6, beta) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -beta)

#creating a bar chart with the terms in each topic
top_terms %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(term, beta), 
             y = beta, fill = factor(topic))) +

  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip()

A bar plot showing the terms in each of the seven topics

range_k <- seq(2, 10, by = 1)  
perplexities <- sapply(range_k, function(k) {
  model <- LDA(dtm, k = k, control = list(seed = 1))
  perplexity(model)
})

# Plotting perplexities
plot(range_k, perplexities, type = "b", xlab = "Number of Topics", ylab = "Perplexity")

This perplexity plot helps in the selection of the suitable number of topics for the model.
